**Version Used**: https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/commit/d8d7886808a68c720a246b09028f870bc62c30fe

**Steps to Reproduce**:
```cs
using System;
public class C {
    public void M() {
        M(new(M1)); // is bound to Func overload with error
        M(new(M2)); // ok; but ambig error expected
        
        M(new(() => {})); // is bound to Func overload with error
        M(new(() => 1)); // ok; but ambig error expected
        
        M(() => {}); // ok
        M(() => 1); // ok
        
        M(M1); // ok
        M(M2); // ok
    }
    
    void M(Func<int> func) {}
    void M(Action action) {}
    
    void M1() {}
    int M2() => 1;
}
```
([sharplab.io](https://sharplab.io/#v2:))

**Expected Behavior**: ambiguous call error for all cases since `new()` does not contribute to overload resolution.

**Actual Behavior**: the invocation is bound to Func overload regardless

See [codegen of `C.M`](https://sharplab.io/#v2:EYLgtghglgdgNAFxFANgHwAIAYAEGCMALANwCwAUBRgMx4BMOAwhQN4U4d60AyUAzggA8sBAD4cAWQAUAShwBecQG18cHHTXUAumXIBfIA==):
```cs
using System.Collections.Generic;

public class C
{
    public List<int> M() => [1, 2, 3];
}
```

To construct the resulting list the following is emitted:
```cs
int num = 3;
List<int> list = new List<int>(num);
CollectionsMarshal.SetCount(list, num);
...
```
It takes more ceremony to init the local and then use it than if the number of elements was used directly:
```cs
List<int> list = new List<int>(3);
CollectionsMarshal.SetCount(list, 3);
...
```

